{"/service/ndnp/ohi/batch_ohi_geranium_ver02/data/sn84028102/00340580813/1957111401/0712.xml":{"full_text":"2\u2014THE RECORD ,CHARDON, OHIO, NOV. 14, 1957\nTractors&lmplements\nHomelite Chain Saws\nTIRES TUBES\nBATTERIES\nGENERAL RE1\nNewbury Auto Service\nNewbury, Ohio Ph. 520\n|M-\nmIRING\n\u25a0A\nI\n-i.nri V/Wliri\n\u201cTHEY\u2019RE CATCHING ON, BUT THEY CAN\u2019T\nCATCH UP.\u201d That\u2019s how lots of people feel about the\n\u201cnew 1958\u201d cars that are trying to match the Dodge\nSwept-Wing look. These other cars have been lowered\nsome, but still seem high and boxy by comparison. A\nfew are \u201ccatching on\u201d to fins, but they\u2019re years from\nJUNCTION AUTO SALES, INC.\nhot showers\na day!\nW\n\u201ck\n\u2019s-\nHF y\nNew, \u201cfast recovery\u201d electric water heaters produce hot water\nas fast as you can use it. The average 40-gallon model delivers\n72 gallons of hot, hot water in two hours or 420 gallons a day!\nThat\u2019s more than three times the average family\u2019s daily hot\nwater needs! So if you want plenty of hot water\u2014fast, get a \u201cfast\nrecovery\u201d electric water heater now.\nA flameless electric water heater costs less to buy up to 40%\nless than any other kind. And you can install it anywhere. Out\nside of heater always stays cool. No flues or vents are needed.\n__ Chardon\nPolice\n(Omitted from Last Week)\nInvestigations of shop-lifting\nin two Chardon stores and pa\ntrol for Halloween pranksters\nkept Chardon Police busy dur\ning the week ending Nov. 5,\nChief of Police John Bohl re\nported today.\nOn Oct. 29, police provided\nan escort for the Chardon Sa\nvings Bank at 9:40 a.m. At\n10:15 a citation was issued for\nreckless driving to Charles A.\nScullion, 60, of Linesville, Pa.\nHe signed a waiver for $20.50.\nFifteen minutes later police\nanswered a call from Ted Smith\nat the Chardon Hardware store\nin the shopping center. He re\nported a Winchester 94, beaver\nI action 30-30 shotgun taken. Po\u00ad\nlife\ns'J F-4\ndiary\n\u201ccatching up.\u201d And the air suspension offered by some\ncars (at well over $100 extra) can\u2019t compare with the\nsway-free, dip-free ride of Dodge Torsion-Aire (standard\nequipment on all models). So on your way home from\nsomeone else\u2019s new car showing, stop in and compare it\nwith Swept-Wing 58 by Dodge. You\u2019ll see what we mean.\nBBL\n4\nK\nlice said it was shoplifted, and\nnot taken during the preceeding\nnight.\nDuring the morning of Wed\nnesday, Oct. 30, police contin\nued investigation of the Citco\nrobbery, checkng out leads. Dur\ning the afternoon a truck with\nlicense 4 TM 67 was spotted.\nPolice discovered that the num\nber was listed on the \u201chot\nsheet\u201d of wanted vehicles pub\nlished in Cleveland. The man\ndriving the truck was picked\nup as he was making a phone\ncall in the booth at the sputh end\nof the park. Five hours later,\nat 7:30, he was released to the\ncustody of Cleveland police.\nAt 8:30 p.m. Oct. 30 police re\nceived a call to the north end\nof the park on a report of ju-\n*.'v\nhi .is, I\n58 byDODGU\nRts. 322 and 44\nIB\"\nBL\nIt's possible with a fast recovery electric water heater\nSpecial Low Rates\nlllhll\njt 4\n1\nveniles breaking bottles in the\nstreet. The youths were gone\nwhen police arrived, but their\nidentity was discovered later.\nThey do not live in Chardon.\nOn Oct. 31, a call was re\nceived from Richard J. Brown,\nThwing road., who said he had\na great dane at his house not\nbelonging to him. He is keep\ning the dog until the owner\nclaims it. At 7:30 p.m. police\ninvestigated a report of a boy\nthrowing stones at the Roy Par\nsons home on N. Hambden St.\nThe offenders were gone when\npolice arrived.\nA citation was issued to Don\nald G. Haycox, 18, 16 Char\nlotte St., Painesville, charging\nreckless driving, at 8:15 p.m.\nHe signed a waiver for $15.50.\nAn acident injuring Frances\nH. Burr, 32, 142 South St., was\nreported at 11:50 p.m., Oct 31.\nIt occured on Fifth Ave., near\nWashington St., and involved\ncars driven by her and Edward\nHokes, Rt. 2, Chardon. Mrs.\nBurr said she was narked in\nfront of 132 Fifth Ave., and the\nHokes auto came from the east\nand ran into her car. Hokes\nsaid he was driving east of Fifth\nAve. and didn\u2019t see her parked\nbecause there .were no lights\non the Burr auto and because\nlight from a car coming toward\nhim blinded him. Mrs. Tin\ncher, 132 Fifth Ave., a passen\nger with Mrs. Burr, was listed\nas a witness.\ni fi\nChief Bohl said today because\nof the many accidents involving\nvehicles parked along the side\nof streets without any lights, tha\nthe police department will be\ngin issuing citations to drivers\nparkng on the streets after dark\nwithout lights. Parking lights\nare required under village ord\ninance 279, section 67.\nAt 11 a.m. on Nov. 1 police\nanswered a call from Mra. Ther\non Miner 138 Center St., who\nhad locked her house* with the\nkeys inside. Police opened the\nhouse for her.\nAt 12:47 a.m. two intoxicated\npersons were reported on Main\nSt. Picked up were Michael Za\nvatsky, 51, staying in Thomp\nson, and Inez A. Mark. 47,\nCleveland. Both were confined\nin jail on charges of intoxica\ntion and later fined $10 and\ncosts.\nThe next afternoon (Nov 1),\npolice picked up tvJo more in\ntoxicated subjects, Joseph Kur\nosky and Paul Kurosky, Cleve-\nIn Chardon it s\nk I\n4\nIt\u2019s safe, clean and completely automatic \u2014nothing to light,\nnothing to \u201cgo out,\u2019\u2019 nothing to attract curious youngsters.\nwhen you use an electric water heater of\n30-gallon capacity or more. For full information, call your nearest\nIlluminating Company office.\nfinch\nCleaners Dyers\nINC.\nfor ALL Your\nDr/ Cleaning Needs\u2019\nCall for pick-up and\nDelivery Service\n518 Water St.\nPhone 5'21\nland. They were confined in\njail and posted bond eight hours\nlater.\nWalter Dieckoa, Rt, 1 Thomp\nson, reported to police he lost a\nsmall collie dog.. The report was\nmade at 3:58 Nov. 1, and he\nsaid the dog was wearing a\ncollar with a strap attached to\nit.\nAt 4:30 pm. police received\na call from the Earl Franz\nFirestone Store, 434 Water St.\nA Frank M. Fabric, Wilson\nMills Rd., said the hubcaps were\nremoved from his car while\nhe was parked in front of the\nstore.\nOn Nov. 2 at 1 p.m. a call\nwas received from Willard L.\nMcKee, 132 Center St., who re\nported a boxer dog found. He\nsaid he would keep the dog\nuntil someone called for it. An\nhour later later police received\na call from Herbert Drenske,\nGeauga\nTHEATRE\nCHARDON\nThurs, Fri, Sat Nov 14. 15. 16\nCalling all ex-servicemen! their\nwives-sweethearts and all others\nwho need a good laugh!\nJack Lemonn Ernie Kovacs\nKathryn Grant\n(Bing\u2019s new wife)\nArthur O\u2019Connell\nMickey Rooney\nOPERATION\nMAD BALL\nFilmed with-out Army approval\nSun. Mon, Tues Nov 17, 18, 19\n5W The\nama\name\nU\u2019\n#3\nWAKNtH\nDoHsDay,\nMnlW-MHWEddieRKJt\nWed. Nov 20 CLOSED\nThurs, Fri, Sat Nov 21, 22, 23\nAlan Freed Rocky Grazino\nTeddy Randazzo Lois O\u2019Brien\nand all your favorite\nMISTER ROCK\nAND ROLL\nLeigh Snowden\nDick Hartunian\nHOT ROD\nRUMBLE\nDon\u2019t forget: Only one show\nstarting at 7:30 on Mon., Tues,\nand Thurs. nights.\nTreasurer.\n234 N. Hambden St. who said\nhe had found a collie dog. Po\nlice notified the Thompson man\nwho had reported losing a dog\nof that breed. He came to Char\ndon to look at the one at* the\nDrenske residence, but repor\nted it was not his.\nOn Nov. 3 at 11 p.m. a ci\ntation was issued to Kenneth E.\nAlebb, 21, Rt. 4, Chardon, for\nrunning a stop light. He signed\na waiver of $10.50. On Nov. 4\nEdward J. Newel, Warren, pick\ned up some time ago for driving\nBOYS\u2019GRAND PRIZE\nENGLISH\nLIGHTWEIGHT BICYCLE\nFlashy metallic-red color. Has 3\nspeed Sturmy Archer gear shift, lots\nof chrome features, lights, tourist\nbag. plus other extras.\nHere's everything you need for ba\nsic chemistry experiments! 4-panel\nfolding steel cabinet.\nHiller Flying\n